  "texts": [
    "Given b ∈ B and a loop γ: [0, 1] → B with γ(0) = γ(1) = b, consider for each p ∈ M b the unique H-horizontal lift γp: [0, 1] → M with γp (0) = p.Definition 2.7.",
    "The holonomy of the connection H at b ∈ B with respect to the loop γ is the mapM b → M b, p → γp (1).Considering all possible loops based at b, and fixing an identification M b ≃ N coming from a local trivialisation, we obtain the so-called holonomy group, which is naturally a subgroup of the structure group (which is itself a subgroup of ρ(π 1 (B)) ⋉ N).",
    "It is well-defined up to conjugation.For most of the article (except for Section 6), we will be interested in flat connections: the case where H is an integrable distribution.",
    "Let H be a flat connection on M, and fix a fibre M b and an identification M b ≃ N. By flatness, the horizontal lift of piecewise-smooth loops in B based at b is independent of the homotopy class of the loop, and thus gives rise to a well-defined monodromy representation(9) ρ H: π 1 (B) → ρ(π 1 (B)) ⋉ N.Clearly, the image of ρ H must contain ρ(π 1 (B)), but there may be also a translational part.",
    "We will often be dealing with flat connections whose monodromy ρ H equals the twisting homomorphism ρ.Example 2.8."
